Last-Modified: Mon, 20 Jan 1997 14:58:25 GMT
Content-Length: 2887
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>CNR-IAN Genoa, Italy Robotics Dept.: Manipulation</title>
<base href="http://www.ian.ge.cnr.it/robotics/manip.htm">
</head>

<body background="/icons/cnrfilig.gif">
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="4" cellpadding="4">
    <tr>
        <td width="600"><p align="center"><a
        href="http://www.ian.ge.cnr.it"><font size="4"><b>CNR-IAN</b></font></a><font
        size="4"><b> <img src="/icons/arrow.gif" width="18"
        height="18"> </b></font><a
        href="http://www.ian.ge.cnr.it/robotics"><font size="4"><b>Robotics
        Department </b></font></a><font size="4"><b><img
        src="/icons/arrow.gif" width="18" height="18"></b><b><blink>
        Manipulation </blink></b></font></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>In the area of robot control, our studies have mainly centred
on learning control, dynamic control of manipulation by means of
co-operating robots or robot hands, and co-ordinated head/eye
control.</p>

<p>The problem of hybrid position/force learning control has been
addressed within the scope of constrained mechanical systems.
This approach allows simple modelling of the interaction between
robot and environment (though only in the case of stiff grasp),
and makes it possible to formulate a vast class of robotic tasks,
including co-ordinated manipulation tasks. </p>

<p>The effectiveness of the control schemes proposed has been
shown through dynamic simulation experiments, including both the
constrained motion of a single manipulator and the case of
multiple robots handling a common object.</p>

<p>Another study addresses the problem of co-ordinated control in
a robotic head/eye system. A quantitative analysis of the
sensitivity of turning images into world co-ordinates has been
carried out, achieving some preliminary results. The analysis has
subsequently been used to design suitable control schemes which
tackle the basic problem of tracking features moving in space. </p>

<hr>

